Gemini said
It looks like you’ve hit the classic "Nerd Font Paradox": Waybar looks great because it's pulling from your system-wide symbols, but your terminal (and Starship) is struggling because it doesn't know which actual letters to pair those symbols with.

Here is the situation: You have the Symbols-only Nerd Font package installed. This is great for apps like Waybar that can "fallback" to these symbols, but for Starship to render correctly in a terminal, your terminal emulator (like Alacritty, Kitty, or Foot) needs to be told exactly what to display.

The Issue: Symbols vs. Patched Fonts
Currently, you have ttf-nerd-fonts-symbols installed. This contains only the icons. Starship usually expects your terminal to be using a Patched Font—a font where the icons are baked directly into the typeface (e.g., JetBrains Mono + Icons).

Option 1: The "Patched Font" Route (Recommended)
Instead of relying on a separate symbols-only package, install a specific Nerd Font and set your terminal to use it. This is usually the most stable way to get Starship looking perfect.

Install a popular patched font:

Bash
sudo pacman -S ttf-jetbrains-mono-nerd
(Other popular choices: ttf-cascadia-code-nerd, ttf-fira-code-nerd)

Update your terminal config:
Open your terminal configuration file (e.g., ~/.config/alacritty/alacritty.toml or ~/.config/kitty/kitty.conf) and set the font family to:
JetBrainsMono Nerd Font

Option 2: The "Fallback" Route (The Lazy Fix)
If you love your current terminal font (like DejaVu or Noto) and don't want to change it, you need to ensure Fontconfig is correctly layering the symbols on top of your text.

Create (or edit) ~/.config/fontconfig/fonts.conf:

XML
<?xml version="1.0"?>
<!DOCTYPE fontconfig SYSTEM "fonts.dtd">
<fontconfig>
 <alias>
  <family>monospace</family>
  <prefer>
    <family>Your-Current-Font-Name</family>
    <family>SymbolsNerdFont Mono</family>
  </prefer>
 </alias>
</fontconfig>
Why is Starship still broken?
Starship uses specific Powerline and Nerd Font v3 glyphs. Since your pacman output shows version 3.4.0-1, you have the newest icons, but if your terminal isn't explicitly told to use SymbolsNerdFont, it will just show those annoying empty boxes ([?]).

Quick Check:
Run this command in your terminal. If you don't see a folder icon, your terminal emulator is the bottleneck:
echo -e "\uf07b"

