what's more modern? alacritty.toml or alacritty.yml ?

Gemini said
Definitely .toml.

Alacritty officially made the switch from .yml to .toml in late 2023 (starting with version 0.13.0). If you are using the latest version on Arch (which you almost certainly are, given it's a rolling release), .toml is the standard.

Why the change?
The developers moved to TOML because:

Performance: TOML is faster and simpler for the program to parse.

Human-Friendly: It avoids the "indentation hell" of YAML where one missing space breaks the entire config.

Consistency: Much of the Rust ecosystem (which Alacritty is built with) uses TOML by default.

How to migrate (The Fast Way)
If you currently have an old alacritty.yml and want to modernize it, you don't have to rewrite it by hand. Alacritty has a built-in migration tool:

Bash
alacritty migrate
This will automatically create a backed-up version of your .yml and generate a fresh alacritty.toml for you.

Example Font Config (TOML)
Since we were talking about your Nerd Fonts earlier, here is how the font section should look in your new alacritty.toml if you decide to install a patched font like JetBrains Mono:

Ini, TOML
[font]
size = 11.0

[font.normal]
family = "JetBrainsMono Nerd Font"
style = "Regular"

[font.bold]
family = "JetBrainsMono Nerd Font"
style = "Bold"
