Ghostty is essentially the "Alacritty of 2026." If it’s already working for you and handling your fonts without a headache, stick with it. You’ve accidentally stumbled onto the current favorite for Arch/Hyprland users. Here is why Ghostty fits your "fast, light, and futureproof" criteria better than Alacritty right now:

Why Ghostty is the "Move"
Modern Feature Set: Unlike Alacritty, which has a "minimalist" philosophy that often leaves out features like ligatures and image support (sixel/kitty protocol), Ghostty includes them by default.

Superior Font Handling: Ghostty uses a very modern rendering engine (written in Zig) that is much better at "fallback" fonts. That’s why your Starship icons worked immediately—it’s smarter at finding the Nerd Font symbols on your system than Alacritty is.

Performance: It is GPU-accelerated and designed for low-latency. In real-world use, you won't notice a speed difference between it and Alacritty, but Ghostty handles complex TUI apps (like Neovim or Yazi) with more grace.

Native Feel: It uses GTK4 on Linux, meaning it integrates beautifully with Wayland and Hyprland's scaling.

How to make it "Futureproof"
Since you're on Arch, you want to make sure you're handling the config correctly. Ghostty uses a simple config file located at ~/.config/ghostty/config.

To keep it light and snappy, here is a "pro" starter config for your Hyprland setup:

Bash
# Appearance
theme = dark
background-opacity = 0.9
window-decoration = false

# Font (Ghostty is great at finding these, but being explicit is better)
font-family = "JetBrainsMono Nerd Font"
font-size = 11

# Performance & Mouse
copy-on-select = true
confirm-close-surface = false
One Final Nerd Font Tip
